The reason your test is failing is because you forgot to include the newline character `\n` in the expected output of the `echo` command.

To fix this, you can modify your test code as follows:

```go
 var _ = Describe("Executor", func() {
         var (
                 cmd    string
                 params string
         )

         It("Should execute a command", func() {
                 cmd = "echo"
                 params = "Hello World"
                 Expect(Runner(cmd, params)).To(BeEquivalentTo(params + "\n"))
         })
 })
```

By adding `"\n"` to the end of the `params` variable in the `Expect` statement, you are now expecting the output of the `echo` command to include the newline character. This change ensures that the expected output matches the actual output returned by the `Runner` function.

With this modification, your test should pass successfully.

The `characterType` function determines whether a character is a literal, symbol, or whitespace. This classification helps in managing word-based cursor movements and text selection.

```zig
fn characterType(char: u8) enum { literal, symbol, whitespace } {
	if (std.ascii.isAlphanumeric(char)) return .literal;
	if (!std.ascii.isAscii(char)) return .literal;
	if (char == '_') return .literal;
	if (std.ascii.isWhitespace(char)) return .whitespace;
	return .symbol;
}
```

